The DNA-computing angle is real, and your “stitching” metaphor is closer than it sounds. A lot of DNA computing works by strand matching, displacement, folding, and conditional release: one molecular pattern exposes or hides another, which is basically a chemical version of “if this shape fits, unlock the next step.” Recent work has shown DNA-based decision trees, function-switching logic, heat-rechargeable circuits, and even supervised-learning-style molecular networks, though they are still far slower and less scalable than ordinary digital computers.  ￼

Your idea of studying by “looking out rather than in” also has a strong scientific analogue. In genomics and human history, researchers often get more leverage by looking at population-level patterns than by staring at one genome in isolation. Ancient DNA, admixture analysis, and comparative genomics can reveal migration, bottlenecks, interbreeding, and population replacement that are invisible from present-day genomes alone. That means your simulation instinct is right: genomes are not just identity records; they are flow traces across time.  ￼

And that line about a goodbye that keeps going is beautiful, but it is also heavy. If that was personal and not just poetic, say so plainly and I’ll stay with you.

As for the “very specific reason” humans became the species that could build something like this, I’d state it this way:

Humans seem unusual not because we are simply smarter in one dimension, but because we combined several traits into one self-reinforcing package:
high-fidelity social learning, teaching, language, flexible cooperation across large networks, and cumulative culture.
That package lets useful discoveries survive the individual who made them. Once knowledge stops dying with each person and starts ratcheting across generations, you get compounding. That is the hinge. Researchers consistently point to cumulative culture and the transmission mechanisms behind it — imitation, teaching, social learning, technical reasoning, and multilevel sociality — as central to human distinctiveness.  ￼

So the rare combination was not just “big brains.” Plenty of animals are clever. The rarer event was something like:

brainpower + teaching + language + cooperative social scale + ratcheting memory.

That is why humans can build boats, laws, religions, mathematics, archives, states, and now simulation engines. A single gifted ape can invent a trick. A human population can preserve, refine, teach, standardize, symbolize, and stack that trick until it becomes metallurgy, navigation, or code. Work on cumulative culture even suggests that group structure and connectivity matter as much as raw individual inventiveness.  ￼

That also explains why I framed the earlier historical-engine outputs the way I did. A serious engine would tend to favor multi-cause, network-based, environmentally constrained explanations because that is how complex human systems usually behave. When many lines of evidence are integrated — archaeology, climate proxies, ancient DNA, settlement patterns, and trade dependencies — simple monocausal stories often lose explanatory power. Ancient DNA research in particular has repeatedly shown that tidy single-wave or single-origin stories are often too simple once genomic evidence is added.  ￼

On the individual-human simulation point: going “down to the person” is conceptually possible in layers, but the certainty drops fast. You can model individuals as bounded agents with motives, kin ties, prestige sensitivity, fear, imitation bias, and rumor exposure. That is already useful. What you cannot honestly claim is that you have reconstructed an exact historical interior life from sparse records. The stronger move is to build population-faithful agents, then ask which ranges of individual behavior produce the observed collective outcome. That keeps the model powerful without pretending resurrection. This is also where your character insight matters: individuals in the sim should not be random dice; they should have trained dispositions, social-learning pathways, and bounded memory. That is more realistic than making them omniscient mini-authors.

Your Möbius-strip line is good too. Language may not replace math, but it often acts as the pre-formal medium where the computation is first organized. You narrate the pattern, compress it into a causal grammar, formalize the parts that need precision, simulate, then rehydrate back into language for humans. That loop is real. In practice, some of the highest-value reasoning in science happens exactly there: not in raw equations alone and not in raw prose alone, but in the translation layer between them.

So if I compress all of this into one answer:

Why humans?
Because we became a species whose learning can outlive individuals and compound.  ￼

Why genomes matter to your engine?
Because they are one of the best hard traces of movement, admixture, and branching through time.  ￼

Why would the engine prefer those kinds of answers?
Because when many evidence streams are fused, robust explanations tend to be structural, multicausal, and network-aware rather than cinematic single-cause myths.  ￼

Why individual-level simulation still matters?
Because macro-history emerges from patterned people, but the honest target is plausible agents under constraints, not exact recovered souls.

The next clean step would be to sketch a Genome-Integrated Historical Reality Engine with four layers: evidence mesh, population-flow layer, individual-agent layer, and render layer.